description.narrative:
The project has to contribute to the following impact and must achieve the outcomes and outputs as stated below.

The project must contribute to the following objective:
- Contribute to end hunger (SDG2).

The proposed project must contribute to the following long-term impacts: 
- Promote agricultural growth;
- Create ecologically sustainable food systems;
- Water efficiency in agriculture increased.

Medium-term impacts that will contribute to this: 
(I) Education system (TVET/HE) is of good quality, relevant and accessible (SDG4);
(II) Partnerships between persons and organiations are inclusive and sustainable (SDG 17);
(III) Organisations key to (sectoral) inclusive development of partner countries are strenthened by inflow of enhanced workforce. 

Outcome:
(A) TVET/HE organisations (in the selected partner countries and in NL) perform better their core tasks, firmly embedded in their environment (in line with country/regional specific labour market needs & aiming at inclusiveness). 

To that end, the following outputs must be achieved by the end of the project:

(1) Increase the quality of the educational programmes of ATVETs in the horticultural sector.

1.1 A-TVET staff carried out a labour market needs assessments for the horticultural industry and an educational assessment on existing (agriculture) teaching methodologies and curricula at relevant Horticulture Training Institutions;
1.2 Revised and newly developed accredited (by TVETA and Qualified by KNQA) market driven and gender sensitive (blended learning) curricula and short courses with a specific focus on application of practical skills through incubation projects in collaboration with the private sector and TVETA and KNQA, and TVET-CDACC;
1.3 ATVET training infrastructure and facilities can support practical field trials by students and blended learníng online courses;
1.4 Students "trained on the job" as part of the incubation projects that are integrated in the horticulture curricula
1.5 Career guidance programme integrated in curricula developed and implemented.

(2) Increased institutional capacity to implement gender transformative Competence Based horticulture programmes.

2.1 A-TVET staff trained on agricultural teaching skills to review, develop, deliver, and access competency-based, market relevant and inclusive curicula together with private sector;
2.2 A-TVET staff trained on practical skills and learning processes, to be able to facilitate practical skill development among students and incubation projects with a focus on application of skills;
2.3 Blended learning skills of A-TVET staff improved to develop and implement e-learning teaching methods;
2.4 A-TVET management and staff trained on gender mainstreaming and inclusivity in teaching;
2.5 Training of Trainers program (TOT) for ATC's, County polytechnics, TVCs, other TVETs and the horticulture community in the neighbourhood of the 3 ATVETS to roll out lessons learned.

(3) Established and sustained triple helix horticulture innovation platform.

3.1 TVETS, public, private stakeholders and sector organizations (FPEAK, HCDA) establish working groups and e-platforms per horticulture commodity under the platform and develop a strategy for a horticulture Triple helix innovation platform (alumni, youth, women and marginalized groups are represented in the platform);
3.2 An accredited "work place program" for teaching and training staff and apprenticeship programme for students in collaboration with the horticultural industry (and alumni) developed with help of the triple helix platform;
3.3 A satellite program for practical training per horticulture commodity at selected locations (model farms, in-company or public fields) is developed in collaboration with private sector, alumni, educational institutions and (county)government, with help of the triple helix platform;
3.4 Teaching staff "trained on the job/industry attachments" as part of the "work place program" and "satellite program" in the horticultural industry with focus on practical skills;
3.5 Students "trained on the job" as part of the "satellite program" and "apprenticeship programme" in the horticultural industry with focus on practical skills;
3.6 Mentorship programme as part of the horticulture triple helix platform to support incubates & youth in their innovation project or starting Enterprise;
3.7 Female talent development program at ATVETs is developed in collaboration with the industry and implemented;
3.8 Monitoring and evaluation mechanisms at ATVETs strengthened, to monitor practical skill competence of students (and staff), including tracer studies and out of school learning processes (apprenticeship program and satellite program).
